x4freetext: Experiment performed at the Los
Alamos Neutron Science Center (LANSCE)using 800 MeV
proton linac
Thin-walled aluminum cylinder with kapton windows on
both ends was used as an argon gas target cell.
Diameter of the cell was 3.81-cm and length 6.35-cm.
Kapton window was 0.127-mm thick.The gas cell was
placed at the center of the GEANIE array, with the
neutron beam passing through the Kapton foils. The
natural Ar gas pressure was maintained at about 2.75
atm.
Single coaxial detector of the GErmanium Array
for Neutron Induced Excitations (GEANIE) with the
best energy resolution, peak-to-background ratio, and
timing was used for gamma ray detection. Detector was
placed at theta= 77.1 deg relative to the beam axis.
GEANIE was located 20.34 m from the spallation target
at the Weapons Neutron Research facility 60R flight
path.
Incident neutron energy was determined using
time-of-flight technique. Sharp gamma flash from each
proton pulse at the spallation target was used as
reference t=0 time.
Pulsed neutron beam was produced via
spallation on a natural W target by an 800-MeV proton
linear accelerator beam. The average proton beam
current at the spallation target was about 1 - 2 mu-A.
The neutron beam structure contained 625 mu-s long
`macropulses` driven by two of every three such
macropulses from the accelerator for an average rate
of 40/s. Each macropulse consisted of `micropulses`
spaced every 1.8 mu-s, each <1 ns long. The pulsed
beam allowed incident neutron energies to be
determined using the time-of-flight technique.
Correction for non-isotropic angular distribution was
made. The AVALANCHE code was used to calculate the
angular distribution for all of the measured
transitions. The angular distribution correction
factor was determined by comparing the calculated
angular distribution at a particular angle to an
isotropic assumption.
